.frame_delay
    LDX zp_frame_progress  \ Frame-rate regulator (busy-wait). Called once per main_loop iteration. zp_frame_progress accumulates 'work done this frame' (e.g. update_bullets does `INC zp_frame_progress` twice per active bullet, get_ready_overlay bumps it once per other frame). At entry, zp_frame_progress starts at zp_game_speed (set by the user's Speed option in `options.BAS` line 700: `?&92 = 120 + S%*30`, so 120 = slow .. 240 = fast; the BREAK cheat in Loader2 line 1310 sets it to 252). The busy loop runs (256 - X) outer iterations × 256-cycle inner loop, so the delay is INVERSELY proportional to zp_frame_progress: heavy frames (high X) get short delays, idle frames (X near zp_game_speed) get long delays — total frame time is roughly constant. The `CPX #&64 / BCS / LDX #&FE` guard handles the overflow case where so much work happened that zp_frame_progress wrapped past 255 to a small value (< 100): substitute X=&FE for a fixed minimum delay (~2 outer iterations) rather than the paradoxically-long (256-X) the underflowed value would imply. After the wait, zp_frame_progress is reset to zp_game_speed for the next frame.
    CPX #&64
    BCS L13C4
    LDX #&FE
.L13C4
    LDY #&00
.L13C6
    INY
    BNE L13C6
    INX
    BNE L13C4
    LDA zp_game_speed
    STA zp_frame_progress
    RTS

